### Description
When registering a service with a sidecar, envoy logs about duplicate addresses if the sidecar_service port matches an already existing sidecar service port. This PR will help users understand why their sidecar service isn’t working before having to check the envoy/consul logs.

### Testing & Reproduction steps
* Define two services in which the side car service port match.
 
frontend
```
service {
  name = "frontend"
  port = 6060
  connect {
    sidecar_service {
      port = 20000
      proxy {
        upstreams = [
          {
            destination_name = "backend"
            local_bind_port  = 50000
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}
```
web
```
service {
  name = "web"
  port = 7000
  connect {
    sidecar_service {
      port = 20000
      proxy {
        upstreams = [
          {
            destination_name = "db"
            local_bind_port  = 51000
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}
```


* Register the service: **consul services register frontend.hcl**. The service will be registered.
* Start envoy for frontend: **consul connect envoy -sidecar-for frontend -admin-bind localhost:19001**
* Register the next service: **consul services register web.hcl**. 
* Start envoy for web: **consul connect envoy -sidecar-for web**.
* You will see both Consul and Envoy logs have similar errors:
`error="rpc error: code = Internal desc = Error adding/updating listener(s) public_listener:0.0.0.0:20000: cannot bind '0.0.0.0:20000': Address already in use`


### Links
I was originally looking at [this issue](https://github.com/hashicorp/consul/issues/11571) to see if duplicate ports between a service's sidecar port and upstream would cause this. After trying to repro, I noticed the upstream is still accessible with duplicate ports in that scenario. I think that error is from duplicate sidecar services as well, but will follow up to check.


### PR Checklist

* [*] test coverage passed without update
* [ ] external facing docs updated
* [*] not a security concern

